response 2.response_text:
The admissions page states, "When applying to our graduate program, you must select one as your ultimate degree objective. The choice will affect your path into and through our graduate program. However, students pursuing the PhD as their ultimate degree objective need not but may pursue the MSE simultaneously and typically with no additional effort... And students pursuing the MSE as their ultimate degree objective may subsequently apply to pursue the PhD, but with no guarantee of admission."

This indicates that while you select one "ultimate degree objective" (MSE or PhD), it is possible to pursue both the MSE and PhD concurrently if your ultimate objective is PhD, or apply for the PhD later if your ultimate objective is MSE. It doesn't explicitly prohibit applying to two *different* MSE programs (academic tracks) within the ECE department at the same time, but it does state you "must also choose a first and second choice academic track to apply to." This implies you are applying to one "program" (MSE or PhD) but can specify preferences for tracks within that program.
